        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-02-02T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-02-02T18:00:00-05:00" n="713" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d713">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/1–645: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-02-02T19:00:00-04:00">February 2, 1945—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>181. The Department leaves to your discretion the matter of making an informal
                    oral approach in regard to political prisoners in Sinkiang as described in your
                    despatch no. 58 of January 6, but suggests that, if you decide to make the
                    approach, you may wish first to obtain the latest information on the subject
                    from our Consul at Tihwa.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
